{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7dd0b2ff-ad4f-4f34-ac90-bd472222fa90","content":"Here's the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  --treenode-filter \"/**/*[TestCategory=Integration]\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Switch mapping:**\n\n| VSTest | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|\n| `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` | `--treenode-filter \"/**/*[TestCategory=Integration]\"` |\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\n**Prerequisites** — your test project needs these NuGet packages:\n\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump`\n\nAnd to use `dotnet test` (rather than invoking the test host directly), set this in your project file:\n\n```xml\n<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n```\n\n> **Note:** The filter syntax changed — `--treenode-filter` uses a path-based format (`/**/*[Property=Value]`). Adjust `TestCategory` to match whatever trait name your framework uses (e.g., MSTest uses `TestCategory`, xUnit uses `Category`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0368925a-2eb8-4062-bfbe-e86b552502de","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform (the new `dotnet test` integration or direct executable), the CLI switches change:\n\n1. `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` → `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` (same with dotnet test, or `--treenode-filter` for the native runner)\n2. `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` (built-in)\n\n\n3. For code coverage, the syntax shifts to `--collect \"Microsoft.CodeCoverage;Format=cobertura\"` or the simpler `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n4. Crash and hang diagnostics map to `--crashdump` and `--hangdump` respectively, with timeout settings like `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can either use `dotnet test` with the new integration (available in .NET 9 and later) or invoke the runner directly, each with slightly different flag syntax. So for .NET 8 specifically, I need to clarify whether they can use `dotnet test` at all — it requires either .NET 9+ or enabling preview features with `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in the project file. If they can use `dotnet test`, the VSTest-style arguments get translated to the Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents, but if not, they'd need to run the test executable directly instead. The cleanest answer for Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8:\n\nOption A: Run the test host directly (after building):\n```\ndotnet build\n./TestProject --treenode-filter \"/**/Category=Integration\" --report-trx --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura --crashdump --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nOption B: Use `dotnet test` with the Microsoft.Testing.Platform integration enabled:\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/Category=Integration\" --report-trx --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura --crashdump --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nFor `dotnet test` to work with MTP arguments, I can either use the `-- --arg` syntax to pass them through, or enable `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in the project file so `dotnet test` uses the MTP protocol directly. I need to verify the exact filter syntax though—it should be path-based like `/**/TestCategory=Integration` rather than the category format I initially wrote. Generating comparison table...","outputTokens":1832},"id":"68492838-e575-457b-998a-ed32ccb279fd","timestamp":"2026-04-07T13:06:22.590Z","parentId":"919baf18-bc87-4fec-bc91-a93ae7a20fa2"}
